</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Abdominal complications affect more than 80% of patients who undergo hematopoietic stem cell transplantation (HSCT) for treatment of benign or malignant hematologic disease and some solid tumors. HSCT can be performed using cells from bone marrow, peripheral blood, or umbilical cord blood. These stem cells may be from the patient him- or herself (autologous transplant), from relatives or nonrelatives with very similar human leukocyte antigen (allogeneic transplant), or from an identical twin (syngeneic transplant). Posttransplantation complications are classified according to the amount of time elapsed between transplantation and onset. Complications that occur during the first 100 days are divided into preengraftment phase complications (≤30 days after transplantation) and early posttransplantation phase complications (31–100 days after transplantation) and include infectious and noninfectious conditions such as hepatic veno-occlusive disease (VOD), hemorrhagic cystitis, neutropenic colitis, benign pneumatosis, and acute graft-versus-host disease (GVHD). Hepatic VOD, neutropenic colitis, and acute hemorrhagic cystitis are associated with the pretransplantation conditioning regimen. After the first 100 days, chronic GVHD and lymphoproliferative disease are the main complications. Computed tomography and ultrasonography are the primary imaging techniques used in HSCT patients and can help make an early diagnosis, grade the severity of impact, and (if necessary) recommend further investigations to confirm the diagnosis.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.342135046">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.342135046">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig1a.jpeg" height="897" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Hepatic VOD (biopsy proved). <b>(a)</b> Abdominal gray-scale US image of the hepatic vein in a 25-year-old man with acute myeloid leukemia (AML) who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 18 days earlier shows minimal ascites (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Duplex Doppler US image of the hepatic vein shows normal findings. <b>(c, d)</b> Abdominal gray-scale <b>(c)</b> and duplex Doppler <b>(d)</b> US images obtained in a 32-year-old man with Hodgkin lymphoma who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 15 days earlier show diffuse gallbladder wall thickening (arrow in <b>c</b>) and narrowed and monophasic flow in the right hepatic vein <b>(d)</b>, findings that represent hepatic VOD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig1b.jpeg" height="897" width="887" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Hepatic VOD (biopsy proved). <b>(a)</b> Abdominal gray-scale US image of the hepatic vein in a 25-year-old man with acute myeloid leukemia (AML) who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 18 days earlier shows minimal ascites (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Duplex Doppler US image of the hepatic vein shows normal findings. <b>(c, d)</b> Abdominal gray-scale <b>(c)</b> and duplex Doppler <b>(d)</b> US images obtained in a 32-year-old man with Hodgkin lymphoma who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 15 days earlier show diffuse gallbladder wall thickening (arrow in <b>c</b>) and narrowed and monophasic flow in the right hepatic vein <b>(d)</b>, findings that represent hepatic VOD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig1c.jpeg" height="791" width="801" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span> Hepatic VOD (biopsy proved). <b>(a)</b> Abdominal gray-scale US image of the hepatic vein in a 25-year-old man with acute myeloid leukemia (AML) who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 18 days earlier shows minimal ascites (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Duplex Doppler US image of the hepatic vein shows normal findings. <b>(c, d)</b> Abdominal gray-scale <b>(c)</b> and duplex Doppler <b>(d)</b> US images obtained in a 32-year-old man with Hodgkin lymphoma who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 15 days earlier show diffuse gallbladder wall thickening (arrow in <b>c</b>) and narrowed and monophasic flow in the right hepatic vein <b>(d)</b>, findings that represent hepatic VOD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig1d.jpeg" height="791" width="875" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span> Hepatic VOD (biopsy proved). <b>(a)</b> Abdominal gray-scale US image of the hepatic vein in a 25-year-old man with acute myeloid leukemia (AML) who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 18 days earlier shows minimal ascites (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Duplex Doppler US image of the hepatic vein shows normal findings. <b>(c, d)</b> Abdominal gray-scale <b>(c)</b> and duplex Doppler <b>(d)</b> US images obtained in a 32-year-old man with Hodgkin lymphoma who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 15 days earlier show diffuse gallbladder wall thickening (arrow in <b>c</b>) and narrowed and monophasic flow in the right hepatic vein <b>(d)</b>, findings that represent hepatic VOD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig2a.jpeg" height="684" width="952" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Hepatic VOD (biopsy proved) in a 22-year-old patient with non-Hodgkin lymphoma who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 20 days earlier. Axial contrast material–enhanced multidetector CT images show diffuse hypoattenuating liver parenchyma <b>(a)</b>, periportal edema <b>(b)</b>, and ascites. The hepatic veins are not visible.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig2b.jpeg" height="684" width="923" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Hepatic VOD (biopsy proved) in a 22-year-old patient with non-Hodgkin lymphoma who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 20 days earlier. Axial contrast material–enhanced multidetector CT images show diffuse hypoattenuating liver parenchyma <b>(a)</b>, periportal edema <b>(b)</b>, and ascites. The hepatic veins are not visible.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig3a.jpeg" height="658" width="907" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Hepatic VOD (biopsy proved) in a 45-year-old patient with multiple myeloma. <b>(a</b>–<b>c)</b> Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted MR images show the hepatic parenchyma with diffuse hyperintense signal, narrowed hepatic veins, and splenomegaly. Edema of the gallbladder wall is noted in <b>b</b>. <b>(d)</b> Axial arterial phase MR image obtained with gadolinium-based contrast material shows heterogeneous enhancement of the liver parenchyma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig3b.jpeg" height="639" width="944" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Hepatic VOD (biopsy proved) in a 45-year-old patient with multiple myeloma. <b>(a</b>–<b>c)</b> Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted MR images show the hepatic parenchyma with diffuse hyperintense signal, narrowed hepatic veins, and splenomegaly. Edema of the gallbladder wall is noted in <b>b</b>. <b>(d)</b> Axial arterial phase MR image obtained with gadolinium-based contrast material shows heterogeneous enhancement of the liver parenchyma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig3c.jpeg" height="658" width="968" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Hepatic VOD (biopsy proved) in a 45-year-old patient with multiple myeloma. <b>(a</b>–<b>c)</b> Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted MR images show the hepatic parenchyma with diffuse hyperintense signal, narrowed hepatic veins, and splenomegaly. Edema of the gallbladder wall is noted in <b>b</b>. <b>(d)</b> Axial arterial phase MR image obtained with gadolinium-based contrast material shows heterogeneous enhancement of the liver parenchyma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig3d.jpeg" height="639" width="931" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span> Hepatic VOD (biopsy proved) in a 45-year-old patient with multiple myeloma. <b>(a</b>–<b>c)</b> Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted MR images show the hepatic parenchyma with diffuse hyperintense signal, narrowed hepatic veins, and splenomegaly. Edema of the gallbladder wall is noted in <b>b</b>. <b>(d)</b> Axial arterial phase MR image obtained with gadolinium-based contrast material shows heterogeneous enhancement of the liver parenchyma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig4a.jpeg" height="704" width="918" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Hepatic GVHD (biopsy proved) in a 42-year-old patient with myelodysplastic syndrome who had undergone mismatched allogeneic HSCT 45 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show minimal periportal edema <b>(a)</b> and thickening of the gallbladder wall <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig4b.jpeg" height="704" width="957" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Hepatic GVHD (biopsy proved) in a 42-year-old patient with myelodysplastic syndrome who had undergone mismatched allogeneic HSCT 45 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show minimal periportal edema <b>(a)</b> and thickening of the gallbladder wall <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig5a.jpeg" height="677" width="887" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Hepatic candidiasis in a 22-year-old patient with non-Hodgkin lymphoma who had undergone autologous HSCT 15 days earlier. Abdominal US images of the right <b>(a)</b> and left <b>(b)</b> hepatic lobes show a small hypoechoic lesion with a central hyperechoic area (bull’s-eye sign) (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig5b.jpeg" height="677" width="887" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Hepatic candidiasis in a 22-year-old patient with non-Hodgkin lymphoma who had undergone autologous HSCT 15 days earlier. Abdominal US images of the right <b>(a)</b> and left <b>(b)</b> hepatic lobes show a small hypoechoic lesion with a central hyperechoic area (bull’s-eye sign) (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig6a.jpeg" height="705" width="941" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Hepatosplenic candidiasis in a 22-year-old patient with non-Hodgkin lymphoma. Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(a)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(b)</b> CT images show small hypoattenuating lesions in the liver and spleen, some of which demonstrate peripheral enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig6b.jpeg" height="705" width="934" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Hepatosplenic candidiasis in a 22-year-old patient with non-Hodgkin lymphoma. Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase <b>(a)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(b)</b> CT images show small hypoattenuating lesions in the liver and spleen, some of which demonstrate peripheral enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig7a.jpeg" height="721" width="979" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> GVHD in a 65-year-old patient with AML who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 35 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show diffuse bowel wall thickening with mucosal enhancement (hyperemia), the halo sign, and ascites. Arrow in <b>a</b> = involvement of the stomach, arrows in <b>b</b> = effects on small bowel and colon.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig7b.jpeg" height="710" width="881" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> GVHD in a 65-year-old patient with AML who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 35 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show diffuse bowel wall thickening with mucosal enhancement (hyperemia), the halo sign, and ascites. Arrow in <b>a</b> = involvement of the stomach, arrows in <b>b</b> = effects on small bowel and colon.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig8.jpeg" height="549" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Intestinal GVHD in a 22-year-old patient with non-Hodgkin lymphoma who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 45 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows fold thickening and the halo sign in the small bowel, as well as mesenteric fat stranding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig9a.jpeg" height="607" width="944" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Pseudomembranous colitis in a 54-year-old patient with AML. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show diffuse circumferential colonic wall thickening <b>(a)</b>, the accordion sign (arrows in <b>b</b>), pericolonic fat stranding, and ascites.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig9b.jpeg" height="607" width="931" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Pseudomembranous colitis in a 54-year-old patient with AML. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show diffuse circumferential colonic wall thickening <b>(a)</b>, the accordion sign (arrows in <b>b</b>), pericolonic fat stranding, and ascites.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig10a.jpeg" height="673" width="927" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Neutropenic colitis (typhlitis) in a 34-year-old patient with nodular sclerosing Hodgkin lymphoma who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 6 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show cecal wall thickening <b>(a)</b>, pericolonic fat stranding <b>(b)</b>, and involvement of the terminal ileum (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig10b.jpeg" height="673" width="949" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Neutropenic colitis (typhlitis) in a 34-year-old patient with nodular sclerosing Hodgkin lymphoma who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 6 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show cecal wall thickening <b>(a)</b>, pericolonic fat stranding <b>(b)</b>, and involvement of the terminal ileum (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig11a.jpeg" height="699" width="928" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> <i>P aeruginosa</i> bacteremia in a 52-year-old patient with non-Hodgkin lymphoma who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 22 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show localized small bowel wall thickening <b>(a)</b> with pneumatosis and mesenteric fat stranding <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig11b.jpeg" height="699" width="947" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> <i>P aeruginosa</i> bacteremia in a 52-year-old patient with non-Hodgkin lymphoma who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 22 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show localized small bowel wall thickening <b>(a)</b> with pneumatosis and mesenteric fat stranding <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig12a.jpeg" height="704" width="953" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Benign pneumatosis in a 33-year-old patient with AML who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 80 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images obtained at different window levels show benign pneumatosis in the wall of the ascending, transverse, and descending colon, along with dilated small bowel. The patient underwent corticosteroid therapy for GVHD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig12b.jpeg" height="704" width="922" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Benign pneumatosis in a 33-year-old patient with AML who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 80 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images obtained at different window levels show benign pneumatosis in the wall of the ascending, transverse, and descending colon, along with dilated small bowel. The patient underwent corticosteroid therapy for GVHD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig13a.jpeg" height="611" width="905" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Thrombotic microangiopathy in a 30-year-old patient with chronic myeloid leukemia who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 37 days earlier. Axial nonenhanced <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(b)</b> CT images show increased intraluminal and mucosal attenuation (bleeding), a hypoattenuating submucosal zone, distended small bowel loops, ascites, and mesenteric fat stranding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig13b.jpeg" height="611" width="971" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Thrombotic microangiopathy in a 30-year-old patient with chronic myeloid leukemia who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 37 days earlier. Axial nonenhanced <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(b)</b> CT images show increased intraluminal and mucosal attenuation (bleeding), a hypoattenuating submucosal zone, distended small bowel loops, ascites, and mesenteric fat stranding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig14a.jpeg" height="835" width="802" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Hemorrhagic cystitis in a 26-year-old woman with acute lymphoblastic leukemia who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 3 days earlier. <b>(a)</b> Abdominal US image shows diffuse thickening of the bladder wall and an intraluminal clot. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse enhancement of the bladder wall, ascites, and a right adnexal cyst (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig14b.jpeg" height="635" width="1071" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Hemorrhagic cystitis in a 26-year-old woman with acute lymphoblastic leukemia who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 3 days earlier. <b>(a)</b> Abdominal US image shows diffuse thickening of the bladder wall and an intraluminal clot. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse enhancement of the bladder wall, ascites, and a right adnexal cyst (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig15a.jpeg" height="696" width="952" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> Bilateral nephritis in a 29-year-old patient with AML who had undergone a second allogeneic HSCT procedure 35 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced corticomedullary phase <b>(a)</b> and nephrographic phase <b>(b)</b> CT images show perfusion defects in the cortex (arrow) representing systemic candidiasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig15b.jpeg" height="696" width="924" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> Bilateral nephritis in a 29-year-old patient with AML who had undergone a second allogeneic HSCT procedure 35 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced corticomedullary phase <b>(a)</b> and nephrographic phase <b>(b)</b> CT images show perfusion defects in the cortex (arrow) representing systemic candidiasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig16.jpeg" height="911" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span> Chronic GVHD in a 34-year-old patient with chronic myeloid leukemia who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 100 days earlier. MR enterographic image shows no abnormal findings. However, subsequent biopsy revealed chronic GVHD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig17a.jpeg" height="925" width="899" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> Mononucleosis-like PTLD in a 19-year-old patient with aplastic anemia who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 125 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show cervical <b>(a)</b> and supraclavicular <b>(b)</b> lymphadenopathies (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig17b.jpeg" height="750" width="899" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> Mononucleosis-like PTLD in a 19-year-old patient with aplastic anemia who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 125 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show cervical <b>(a)</b> and supraclavicular <b>(b)</b> lymphadenopathies (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig18a.jpeg" height="539" width="912" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> Recurrence of non-Hodgkin lymphoma in a 45-year-old patient who had undergone autologous HSCT 90 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show bilateral pleural effusion <b>(a)</b> and a hypoattenuating mass <b>(b)</b> in the retrocrural, pleural, and retroperitoneal spaces.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig18b.jpeg" height="539" width="965" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> Recurrence of non-Hodgkin lymphoma in a 45-year-old patient who had undergone autologous HSCT 90 days earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show bilateral pleural effusion <b>(a)</b> and a hypoattenuating mass <b>(b)</b> in the retrocrural, pleural, and retroperitoneal spaces.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig19a.jpeg" height="865" width="949" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Aggressive recurrence of multiple myeloma in a 45-year-old patient who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 1 year earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show liver masses <b>(</b>arrow in <b>a)</b>, solid lesions in the small bowel wall (arrow in <b>b</b>), and massive ascites.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135046/asset/images/large/rg.342135046.fig19b.jpeg" height="865" width="926" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> Aggressive recurrence of multiple myeloma in a 45-year-old patient who had undergone allogeneic HSCT 1 year earlier. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show liver masses <b>(</b>arrow in <b>a)</b>, solid lesions in the small bowel wall (arrow in <b>b</b>), and massive ascites.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135046&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li